To create an image that pops up an alert message when loaded and opens a new tab to google.com when clicked, you can use HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. Here's an example of how you can achieve this:

HTML:

<!-- The image that will pop up the alert message -->
<img src="alert.png" onload="alertPopup()" />

<!-- The alert message that will be displayed -->
<div id="alertMessage">Please click here to open google.com</div>

CSS:

/* The styles for the image and the alert message */
img {
 width: 100%;
 height: 100%;
 object-fit: cover;
 margin: 0;
}
#alertMessage {
 font-size: 1.5em;
 margin-bottom: 1em;
 background-color:#fff;
 padding: 1em;
 border-radius: 10px;
 opacity: 0;
 transition: opacity 0.3s;
}

/* The transition for the alert message to appear and disappear */
#alertMessage.show {
 opacity: 1;
}

JavaScript:

/* The function that will be called when the image is loaded */
function alertPopup(){
 // Display the alert message
 document.getElementById("alertMessage").innerHTML = "<span>Please click here to open google.com</span>";
 setTimeout(() => {
   // Open a new tab to google.com
   window.open("https://www.google.com","_blank");
 }, 1000);
}

In this code, the image is given an onload event listener that calls the "alertPopup()" function when the image is loaded. Inside the function, the alert message is displayed using the document.getElementById() method to retrieve the element with the id "#alertMessage". The function also uses the setTimeout() function to open a new tab to google.com after a delay of 1 second.

Note: In this code, the image is assumed to be located at "alert.png". You will need to replace this with the actual filename of the image you want to use.
